{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/415"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.24,0.11,0.21,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103397"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103397"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department after being involved in a low speed motor vehicle crash. He was the front seat passenger when the car crashed into another that was running a red light. He was wearing his seat belt and can recall the incident clearly. The only complaint he has is pain in his lower abdomen with movement and palpation, and he does not describe any other injuries. On examination his blood pressure is 115/80 mmHg, pulse 86/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and oxygen saturation 98% on room air. A primary and secondary is completed and the only abnormality is some tenderness over his lower abdomen (Image). A CT pan scan does not show any abnormalities. He is monitored for four hours in the short stay observation unit and is able to mobilise with minimal discomfort and no analgesia requirements. Repeated examination is stable with no changes in vital signs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FAST scan","Admit for observation","Admit and repeat CT scan next day","Discharge home with GP follow up","Discharge home and surgical outpatient review"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient is young and otherwise well with a reassuring CT scan and no deterioration after several hours of observation, it would be most appropriate to discharge him home with discharge advice and GP follow up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with GP follow up\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Recent studies have shown minimal association between seat belt signs and hollow viscus injury in patients subjected to blunt trauma if the CT scan performed on admission to the emergency department is negative. Provided the patients are otherwise well they can be discharged home with clear discharge advice and follow up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFAST scan\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The patient has already had a normal CT scan which is a more sensitive test than a FAST scan for identifying free intraperitoneal fluid. A FAST scan is ordinarily done in the acute setting when the patient is not suitable for a CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit for observation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This patient is stable and has had a negative CT scan with no clinical change after several hours, they do not need to be admitted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit and repeat CT scan next day\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This patient is stable and has had a negative CT scan, they do not need to be admitted or have a repeat CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home and surgical outpatient review\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This patient can be discharged home but can be followed up by the GP. They don\u0027t require specialist outpatient review.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with seat belt trauma that are stable and have had a negative CT scan can be discharged home with GP follow up."],"references":["Rinderknecht TN, Salcedo ES, Holcroft JW. Improved Computed Tomography Performance\nin Blunt Abdominal Trauma\u2014Has Our Care Kept Pace? JAMA Surg 2022; 157:778.","Delaplain PT, Tay-Lasso E, Biffl WL, et al. Excluding HollowViscus Injury for Abdominal Seat Belt Sign Using Computed Tomography  JAMA Surg 2022; 157:771-78."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"415"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20091"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20091"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bec2c196-9bf0-43fe-9ff7-495c9de52cc4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bec2c196-9bf0-43fe-9ff7-495c9de52cc4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":384,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85818"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T09:37:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T15:10:39+09: